{
  "text": "In Figure 2 we show a comparison of the present proposal using n = 10 5 and x r = 0.98 with the approximants of Kr\u00f6ger [CITATION_1] , Petrosyan [CITATION_2] , Nguessong et al [CITATION_3] , Marchi and Arruda [CITATION_4] , and Jedynak [CITATION_5] . The formulae used for these approximants are given in the references and in the code in Appendix B. In order to estimate the machine error, i.e., the maximum accuracy which could be obtained from an iterative procedure, we have performed Newton-Raphson iterations until no further convergence is detected. In order be in the attraction zone of the Newton procedure towards the solution, we have employed Kr\u00f6ger's approximant as an initial guess. The mean number of iterations needed over the approximant has been 4.3. Remarkably, in Figure 2 it can be seen that the spline-based procedure reached almost that machine precision in all the domain. In fact, no relevant improvement can be obtained with the spline-based procedure using more subintervals. This accuracy is many orders of magnitude better than that obtained using any other approximant: note that the figure is in logarithmic y-scale.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "123791919",
